# Platform UI split (strict)

This app ships **two UI stacks**. Do not mix Cupertino and Material inside the same screen file.

## iOS (`defaultTargetPlatform == iOS`)

- Use **Cupertino** from `package:flutter/cupertino.dart` for screens and widgets that paint UI (`*_screen.dart` without `_material` suffix, shared chrome).
- **Do not** add `package:flutter/material.dart` to non–`*_material.dart` files under `lib/features/` (enforced by `test/no_material_import_test.dart`).

## Android (`AppPlatform.isAndroid` — see `lib/app/platform.dart`)

- Use **Material 3** from `package:flutter/material.dart` in **`*_material.dart`** files only (screens/widgets dedicated to Android).
- **Do not** import `package:flutter/cupertino.dart` in `*_material.dart` (enforced by `test/no_cupertino_in_material_test.dart`).

## Routing

- `lib/app/router/app_router.dart` must pick `*ScreenMaterial` vs `*Screen` with `AppPlatform.isAndroid` / `isIOS` so each platform only builds its widgets.
- `lib/app/app.dart`: `MaterialApp.router` on Android, `CupertinoApp.router` on iOS.

## Shared logic

- Providers, repositories, models: **no** Flutter UI imports for platform choice; keep logic platform-agnostic.

## Tracker

- Status and audit checklist: `MATERIAL_ANDROID_TRACKER.md`.
